I wouldn't change anything of my life. Maybe, more money and being able to speak Chinese if anything 🤔 but other than that,, everything else made me who I am, which is LMAO a bit cheesy, but it's kinda true u kno. I learned a lot throughout life and its pretty cool :]

because there are other people out there, probably with a worse life and *still* happier than me. I know, life isn't perfect, life probably has more killers on the way for me, but,,,, I've still had fun :) I met u, and we had some fun times together :) I had experiences and played really interesting games, sung songs that I loved and I want to do so much more :D sure, I don't come from the most loving of families, I don't have the best reputation, and I know not a lot of people like me. But, it's my life. I'm having fun, and that's all that matters :] I'm not hurting anyone, and I'm still obeying to rules of society.

I can't lie and say this stuff doesnt make me angry or upset, but I've grown up with it. It's normal to me, and it does make me envious of other families when they support their child or grandchild, actually help out or spend time with them. But,,, it's useless. My mum always tells my brother and I that we're too emotional for this world, and I guess she's right. I dwell too hard on things, and my brother openly cries about these issues. It's something that won't ever go away, but 🤔 🤔 I guess that's just life. My life overall wasnt/isn't a bad experience. I've had really good times, met people, done crazy things, made mistakes and had fun. I've grown up with only my mum, but she's the only parent I'd ever need and want. We've had financial issues, but we save up and learned the value of money. I've been through my edgy phase of doing things solo, but I learned to rely on others. I've spent most of my life blaming myself for these issues; why can't I speak Chinese, my dad isn't interested in me because I'm a bad daughter, I'm lgbt and it's disgusting and it's my fault, I've made people into monsters bc of how I treated them, I don't deserve happiness,, and other bs that fills my head tbh. I've faced a lot of my demons head on, and yet, I'm not gonna cry about it and say my life is hard.
aaaa Idk. I could go on and on about the complicated family rules and expectations,, but I don't think you'd want to read all that lol.

aaa, I guess I worry for his current family. I don't worry too much about the relationship between myself and him, because it's already happened, you know? Any impressions he could've made, he already missed out. He wasn't there when I grew up, he wasn't there on my first day of nursery, primary or high school. He never tried to have any sort of relationship with me, and if I'm being really honest, I don't think he would've kept in touch at all, if his mother never nagged him to. If anything, he would've just erased us from his life, because we're a big burden to him. We suck out his earnings, we ask for things at Christmases and birthdays, and we're just leeches. I remember my mum and his sister were really good friends for a long time. She moved away to live in Hong Kong after a while, and one day abruptly, she just messaged my mum saying that we 'only talk to them when we want something'. They stopped talking now, and ngl,,, i could tell that hurt my mum a lot.

from what my mum would tell me about my dad, that he really wasn't the person he is now and now hearing and seeing everything he does now- it's just so overwhelming, I guess? It worries me in a way because he's literally a father. He messed up once already- does he really want to do it again?

cos I would try to justify him prior to that situation; told myself that he was doing better at his second attempt of being a father and husband. As stated in the title, I believe this documentary, ‘Extinction: the facts’, was poorly handled by the BBC. The BBC is large platform viewed by many, as it consists of educated individuals who are- meant to be- professional. 

However, with the presentation of this documentary I decided to indulge in with my family on a Sunday night, I feel let down by this channel and the people involved. The accusations and lack of responsibility I was shown, was beyond appalling. 

Throughout the show, the main issue I realised merely 30 minutes into the program, was the fact that this show was no longer about the ‘facts’ we were promised: it became a blame game. Scientific research and statistics were presented horribly, especially with how most of the troubles were- as stated- caused by one country in particular; China. It was not mentioned once- but, several times. Even if not mentioned verbally, the program continued to show compilations of wet markets or hunting in China/East Asian countries.

Although, yes, I agree that China is a large source of where this cruelty is happening, I feel as though this was an unfair portrayal of the country and a discriminated view- China is not the sole country responsible for this. We, as a planet, are struggling. As said in the program’s name, it’s meant to be ‘facts’, which instead, was very one sided- not factual. The audience was fed with the ‘facts’ of what you (the BBC) wanted them to hear. 

This causes a very negative impact towards the China/East Asian community; in both the country itself, as well as its people. With the lack of statistics mentioned for other countries- US, Russia, etc- it only adds more fuel to the fire; viewers will believe China is the sole/main reason for  our global issue.

Speaking as  supporter and viewer of the BBC, I feel as though this documentary let me- and many other East Asian audiences- down. I can only hope that you put others into consideration in your next programs.
